defaultWritten evidence submitted by the Mineral Products Association (HOT07)default1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultExecutive Summarydefault1.1.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default Government has got the balance wrong by incentivizing the production of expensive inefficient renewable heat and not incentivizing large scale efficient use of renewable heat.
default1.2.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default The Renewable Heat Incentive is expensive and poorly formulated.
default1.3.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default Renewable energy targets will only be met with the large scale participation of major industrial operations such as cement, lime and asphalt.
default1.4.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default Renewable heat use in mixed biomass/fossil fuel uses needs to be incentivized otherwise incentive payments will move biomass from industries that currently use them to industries that don’t, with no net benefit.
default1.5.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default Government is attempting to address the symptom of heat demand in the domestic sector and little effort is being placed on long term heat consumption minimization. Building ‘thermal mass’ use should be maximized.
default1.6.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default Biomass supply is insufficient to deliver all of the policies and therefore it is most important to utilize the limited supplies in industries that can maximize its potential.
default1.7.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default Government should provide incentives for Waste Heat Recovery for recovering low grade heat in industrial processes that have maximized the recovery of high grade heat. 
default1.8.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default The Government’s carbon price support (CPS) tax should not be a disincentive to using waste heat recovery. At present fossil fuels used in industrial processes which use waste heat recovery to generate electricity would be subject to the CPS tax.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIntroductiondefault2.1.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Mineral Products Association (MPA) is the trade association for the aggregates, asphalt, cement, concrete, dimension stone, lime, mortar and silica sand industries. With the recent addition of The British Precast Concrete Federation (BPCF) and the British Association of Reinforcement (BAR), it has a growing membership of 
defaultover 
default450 companies and is the sectoral voice for mineral products. MPA membership is made up of the vast majority of independent SME companies throughout the UK, as well as the 9 major international and global companies. It covers 100% of GB cement production, 90% of aggregates production and 95% of asphalt and ready-mixed concrete production and 70% of precast concrete production. Each year the industry supplies £9 billion of materials and services to the £120 billion construction and other sectors. Industry production represents the largest materials flow in the UK economy and is also one of the largest manufacturing sectors
default. 
default2.2.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis response relates largely to the MPA Cement and British Lime Association activities which are part of the Mineral Products Association.
default&#xa0;
default3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIs the government taking the right approach to reduce heat energy demand?default3.1.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGovernment has chosen two principle policy approaches:
default3.1.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultto reduce heat demand through energy efficiency
default3.1.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultto decarbonise heat through incentivising certain limited technologies.  
default&#xa0;
default3.2.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGovernment has a
defaultn
default excess of policies to address energy efficiency or reduce greenhouse gas emissions. These numerous policies are creating a cumulative burden of cost on manufacturing sectors such as the UK cement and lime manufacturing
default. This cumulative burden is 
defaultdemonstrated in the MPA evidence to the 
defaultEnvironmental Audit Committee
default. These two sectors are 
defaultexamples of the mineral products 
defaulttargeted directly through ‘command and control’ legislation and economic instruments but these sectors are not provided with the opportunities of incentive schemes that other sectors of the economy benefit from. As such Government has got the balance wrong when it comes to ‘carrots and sticks’ for reducing heat demand and decarbonising heat.
default3.3.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default Cement and lime production cannot benefit from the Renewable Heat Incentive (RHI) because the scheme has three principle limitations:
default3.3.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt does not allow the use of biomass to be supplemented by fossil fuels. This mixed use is necessary in some industries to maintain fuel security of supply and cater for biomass fuel interruptions.
default3.3.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe RHI prescribes technologies that generate ‘metered’ heat. Directly fired operations in kilns or furnaces use heat directly and are not metered via a heat carrier e.g. steam. However, directly fired biomass applications can easily measure the amount of biomass use by measuring the calorific value of the fuel input.
default3.3.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRHI does not incentivize any renewable heat from equipment that is not new. Many industrial processes have long investment life cycles and fuel switching will often, but not always, require new equipment. More likely are modifications to existing equipment. The requirement for the RHI to be applied to new equipment is a significant limitation to biomass heat use in industry, particularly where incremental change is a necessity to minimize production intervention. 
default3.4.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default The Government’s Carbon Price Support tax is designed to tax fossil fuels used for electricity generation. When an industrial process uses Waste Heat Recovery to generate electricity, it is not clear whether it would be subject to the Carbon Price Support tax. This lack of clarity is a disincentive to recover waste heat in industrial processes using fossil fuels.
default3.5.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default defaultIn the industrial sector it is companies with large energy bills that are taking action to minimise their costs, tackle energy and heat efficiency. The UK cement industry has published its ‘
defaultGreenhouse gas strategy to 2050
default’
default.
default 
defaultOutlining an ambitious target of -81%  GHG emissions  by 2050, against 1990, (the Kyoto Protocol baseline year), the UK cement industry has set out for the first time the actions they, and others, need to take to exceed the UK Government’s own -80% aim
default. Government support to assist and accelerate the delivery of this strategy is noticeably absent and without such support the maximum ambition of an 81% decarbonisation of UK cement production by 2050 
defaultmay not be delivered
default.
default&#xa0;
default4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhat progress is the government making on reducing the demand for heat?default4.1.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default 
defaultSome sectors of the economy have already taken considerable early action. The minerals manufacturing sector and in particular cement and lime manufacturers have made considerable improvements to reduce their heat demand and to decarbonise their heat use
default. The UK cement industry has reduced 
defaultabsolute GHG emissions by 54% since 1990 which out strips the UK economy as a whole. Waste derived fuel used to replace traditional fossil fuels in the UK cement industry is now at 40% thermal replacement, biomass is now at 17%, but more could be done with targeted assistance 
defaultfrom Government. Similarly, the UK lime industry has replaced fossil fuels with waste and part biomass waste, but more opportunities exist within the correct framework
default.
default4.2.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhilst it is important to reduce the nation's reliance on fossil fuels across the whole economy
default,
default heat policy should also recognise that the thermodynamics and chemical reactions necessary in some processes require heat to be delivered in a particular way
default, whilst others have fuel limitations due to product quality
default. As with the Carbon Budgets that are enshrined in the Climate Change Act, reducing the demand for heat can be met by reducing the industrial base that relies on heat energy.
default This is unsustainable, and until Government 
defaultcreat
defaulte
default a complimentary relationship
default between GHG/energy policy and i
defaultndustrial 
defaultmanufacturing 
defaultpolicy 
defaultenvironmental policies will continue to erode the competitiveness of the UK manufacturing sector
default. 
default4.3.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default defaultThere are a range of Government policies that are relevant to the demand reduction of heat that span the domestic, commercial and industrial areas of the economy. Policies from planning, through building regulations, to building performance certificates all influence the demand for heat in our built environment. Getting the right balance for both heating and cooling is important. In particular there is a need to get the right balance in the heat policy between the different uses of heat and managing heat. 
default4.4.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Mineral Products Association is somewhat unique in that our members’ activities are broad enough to include the extraction of minerals, the processing of those minerals into construction materials and the design of thermally efficient solutions for commercial and domestic buildings, structures and infrastructure. 
defaultHigh grade heat recovery in the cement and lime industry is already maximised, however, lower grade heat provides some opportunities. Government should do more to investigate and finance heat recovery for low grade opportunities in industry. At present Waste Heat Recovery (WHR) from cement and lime manufacturing processes is uneconomic but with targeted incentives could provide some power.
default4.5.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default defaultThe building fabric in particular represents an area where heat energy demand can be reduced much further through a move to more passive heating and cooling solutions. The proliferation of passive heating and cooling systems utilising the 'thermal mass
default' benefits of heavyweight materials in buildings would have considerable long term benefits for the economy, emissions reduction targets, energy security of supply and help reduce the risk of future overheating in buildings as a consequence of climate change.
default&#xa0;default5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBiomass is deemed a key fuel for heat production from both the cost and GHG perspectives.default&#xa0;default What should be done to ensure methods of calculating biomass GHG balance represent an accurate picture?default5.1.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default defaultIn the UK cement sector, use of fossil fuels accounted for only 
default60
default% of combustion fuel use in 2012, down from 94% in 1998. This means that the cement sector has taken considerable early action in decarbonising its heat demand by switching to waste derived and biomass fuels. The challenge for the future will be to make sure that the biomass fuels remain available to cement and lime manufacturers and are not simply diverted to other areas of the economy that are currently receiving incentive payments via the Renewable Heat Incentive which are inaccessible to the cement and lime operators. Consequently, there is a measurement issue when it comes to deciding whether policies such as the RHI are generating additional biomass heat or 
defaultjust moving the biomass heat consumption from those that don’t currently receive RHI to those that do.
default5.2.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default 
defaultAnnex Idefault illustrates the potential for diverted biomass fuel consumption. It shows that whilst part-biomass fuels have increased consumption in cement manufacture, the use of 100% biomass fuels has not increased at the same rate. The lack of growth of 100% biomass fuels coincides with incentives to use biomass fuels in other sectors and other technologies.
default5.3.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default defaultThere is a debate that encourages CO
default2
default from biomass fuel use to be counted in GHG inventories. However, there is a danger that this will discourage the switch from fossil to biomass fuels. Without the ‘carbon neutrality’ of biomass fuels
default,
default the incentive to switch away from fossil fuels is vastly diminished in some sectors that require heat to be delivered in a particular way e.g. directly in a kiln. Furthermore waste biomass that would otherwise have been landfilled should also retain a ‘carbon neutral’ status to further encourage the maximised use of biomass that is technically or economically too difficult to retrieve for non-fuel uses e.g. recycling.
