default&#xa0;default7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultShould the government take any further specific actions in relation to coolingdefault? 
default7.1.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn the domestic sector there is considerable opportunity to gain benefit from the use of thermal mass in buildings. Thermal mass is a term that describes the ability of a material to store heat
default. To
default be useful in the built environment, the material must also be able to absorb and release heat at a rate roughly in step with a building’s daily heating and cooling cycle. Concrete and masonry products do this 
defaultwell and, being dense materials
default 
defaultthey 
defaultcan also store a lot of heat. Timber absorbs heat too slowly to offer much effective thermal mass and steel conducts heat too rapidly to be in synch
defaultronisation
default with a building’s natural heat flows over the day
default. 
default7.2.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default The amount of CO
default2
default that can be saved from utilising the thermal mass of a building 
defaultdepends on the building type and the way in which its thermal mass is used. In the case of a very heavyweight building, the additional concrete can result in a slightly higher level of embodied
default CO
default2
default, but the operational savings afforded by the thermal mass will typically offset this in a matter of months rather than years. 
default7.3.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFor housing
default,
default the situation is slightly different: The embodied CO
default2
default in a typical masonry home is about 4% higher than an equivalent timber frame home. Studies by Arup and the NHBC Foundation both arrived at this figure. The Arup study went on to look at operational impacts and found that the passive benefits of thermal mass during the heating seasons resulted in CO
default2
default savings that offset the figure of 4% in around 11 years
default.
default7.4.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultConsequently, interventions in the building sector that promote and utilize the benefits of thermal mass to manage heat have the potential to provide long lasting energy efficiency and CO
default2
default reduction opportunities.
